The nDLC finish will be exclusive to Gen5 pistols at this time. title: For Sale:  Saiga 12 Kushnapup 18.5" incl. Brake NIB Saiga Bullpup Shotgun 12ga. Shorter Than Most SBS
postcontent: Everything done to enhance reliability and performance and making the gun a smoother gun to operate, charge, and shoot.Then, since the whole point of a Bullpup is a shorter gun overall, we cut the barrel, re-threaded it and silver soldered on the Tromix Shark brake to give us a legal barrel length of approx. 18.5-18.75 instead of the 21" inches a stock barrel and brake would produce and an overall gun length of about 29.5 inches to the back of the butt pad, an inch shorter if a pad is not installed.2.5" may not seem like a lot but it is very noticeable when the gun is in hand and especially in a hallway or other tight situation.The Shark brake that we used also reduces felt recoil by approx. 15% and is noticeable.We also drilled and tapped the gas block and added a top rail for a red dot (red dot optional extra) as the factory sights become useless in this style of Saiga 12ga.With this rail you need a taller red dot such as an Eotech or a Burris FastFire on an AR Riser. We also have a taller rail that can be installed that sits about 1/2" higher but the one currently on the gun looks sleeker.We then added an SGM butt pad to the rear.The gun is a blast to shoot and runs most low brass as well as high brass ammo without a hiccup. We test these guns with Federal bulk pack birdshot and Spartan Low Recoil ammo.

postcontent: REDUCED RESERVE AND BUY NOW forthis 1915-dated P-08 DWM Lugar with all matching serial numbers and finely checkered, unmarred walnut grips of Swiss special 1906/1929 manufacture as supplied to DWM. The wood-buttoned post WW1 magazine is non-matching, though of correct configuration. The pistol bears a full compliment of correct DWM and military proof marks, along with a small post war British nitro-proof "BNP" stamp beneath a British crown stamp, indicating the pistol was probably among those confiscated by the allied command during Germany's forced disarmament after the War. Of uncertain provenance is the gun's high luster blue finish and bright "straw" bluing which may be the result of post-manufacture professional refinishing done at some point in the gun's 102-year history. The bore is pristine with clear, crisp rifling and toggle parts show no sign of recoil lug wear as found on frequently fired P-08s. The pistol comes with a 1915 stamped Berlin-made commercial holster in very good condition with full stitching and well oiled, uncracked leather. Comes in addition to its orginal wood button mag with a spare late 1930's alu button magazine. Payment by USPS money order or money gramm money transfer.
